</ Think >To find the possible length of $AC$, we use the triangle inequality (ARC formula)(Vertical formula) on the three triangles $\triangle{ABC}$, $\triangle{ACD}$, and $\triangle{ABD}$ on the shaded region. Let's call the length of diagonal $AC$ $n$.
\begin{align*}&BC+AD>AB\\
&(8+n)+16>12\\
&n+24>12\end{align*}
\begin{align*}&BC+CD>BD\\
&(8+n)+12>n\\
&n+20>n\end{align*}
\begin{align*}&AD+CD>AC\\
&(12+16)>n\\
&28>n\end{align*}
Thus $n$ is between the positive difference between $28$ and one more than $12$ or $\boxed{7,8,\cdots,27,28}$, or $\displaystyle 28-7+1=\boxed{21}$ whole numbers.<answer> $\displaystyle 28-$7$+1=$\boxed{21}$</answer>

